  "text": "The LLVM optimization pass pipeline lifecycle involves several key components that work together to build and execute optimization passes:\n\n1. **PassBuilder Class (llvm/include/llvm/Passes/PassBuilder.h, llvm/lib/Passes/PassBuilder.cpp)**: The PassBuilder class is the central orchestrator that constructs optimization pipelines. The critical method is `buildPerModuleDefaultPipeline()` (line 258 in the header) which builds the default O2 optimization pipeline for per-module optimization. This method coordinates the construction of module simplification and module optimization pipelines by calling into PassBuilderPipelines functions.\n\n2. **PassManager Template Class (llvm/include/llvm/IR/PassManager.h)**: The PassManager template class (defined at line 162) is the core pass execution engine. It's instantiated as PassManager<Module> and PassManager<Function>, and manages the actual execution of passes over the IR units. It provides the infrastructure for running passes in sequence and managing their analysis results through AnalysisManager.\n\n3. **PassBuilderPipelines Implementation (llvm/lib/Passes/PassBuilderPipelines.cpp)**: This file contains the functions that actually assemble the default optimization pipelines. Key functions include:\n   - `buildFunctionSimplificationPipeline()` (line 592): Constructs per-function canonicalization and simplification passes\n   - `buildModuleSimplificationPipeline()` (line 1091): Constructs module-level canonicalization and simplification passes  \n   - `buildModuleOptimizationPipeline()` (line 1478): Constructs module-level optimization passes including vectorization and other aggressive transformations\n\n4. **PassRegistry.def (llvm/lib/Passes/PassRegistry.def)**: This file registers all standard passes available in LLVM's pass registry. It uses preprocessor macros to define passes for different IR levels (MODULE_PASS, CGSCC_PASS, FUNCTION_PASS, etc.). Each pass entry specifies a string name that can be used to reference the pass and the constructor call to instantiate it.\n\n5. **DeadStoreElimination Example (llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/DeadStoreElimination.cpp, llvm/include/llvm/Transforms/Scalar/DeadStoreElimination.h)**: The DSEPass class (defined in the header at line 28) is a concrete example of a function pass that implements dead store elimination using MemorySSA. It's registered in PassRegistry.def (line 433) as FUNCTION_PASS(\"dse\", DSEPass()), making it available for inclusion in optimization pipelines.\n\nThe pipeline lifecycle flows as follows: (1) PassBuilder::buildPerModuleDefaultPipeline() is called with an OptimizationLevel, (2) it invokes the pipeline building functions from PassBuilderPipelines.cpp which construct the appropriate pass pipeline, (3) passes are registered via PassRegistry.def with their string names and constructors, (4) the resulting ModulePassManager is created and executed over IR units using the PassManager template class infrastructure, and (5) individual passes like DSEPass run their transformations on the IR."
}

